featured_reviews.review_id: Walked to the Moorish Mosque. It's a copy of the Grand Mosque in Marrakech, Morocco. Built by Maharaja Jagatjit Singh. Kapurthala used to be 60% Muslim. All of them have migrated to Pakistan during Partition in 1947. Now the Muslim population is 2%. The wooden domed ceiling is also a copy of the Grand Mosque in Morocco. It's the only Moroccan style mosque in India.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Lovely architecture, something that's only available when we travel overseas. Was sad to see that it's not maintained and in such a sorry state.

This museum can be great attraction to this sleepy town if maintained and promoted properly. Would you like request Punjab Government to take note and save this historical monument. 

Everyone else, if you are heading to Ludhiana from Amritsar, do take a small detour and visit the place.

We also love the bhelpuri right outside the venue on the opposite corner.

featured_reviews.review_translated_text:
Among the famous historical places of Punjab, the Moorish Mosque of Kapurthala holds a special place. This historical building is a unique symbol of religious tolerance. This is a huge mosque which was built by a non-Muslim. Today it is counted among the famous tourist destinations of Punjab. It has been constructed on the lines of the Grand Mosque of Marrakesh, Morocco.
Actually, Maharaja Jagatjit Singh of Kapurthala princely state had gone to Morocco in the year 1925. There he liked the huge mosque of Marrakesh very much. He decided to build a similar mosque in his state. Its construction started in the year 1927 and after 3 years of hard work it was completed in 1930. At that time, approximately Rs 6 lakh was spent on its construction. At that time, 60 percent of the population of the princely state of Kapurthala was Muslim and this mosque was a gift from the Maharaja to his subjects.
The interior dome of the mosque was decorated by artists from the Mayo School of Art, Lahore. A wooden model of the Moorish mosque is also placed at the entrance of the Lahore Museum. This mosque is a national monument, which is maintained by the 'Archaeological Survey of India'.
Its magnificent artwork is similar to the Grand Mosque located in Morocco. The mosque, built on the design of the famous French architect M Monteux, has been protected as a national monument. This mosque is a wonderful example of French architecture. The verses of the Quran are written on it in Arabic script.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Indeed an impressive monument and according to me the only full fledged mosque built in true Moorish architecture style.
The mosque is a pure gem in the list of monuments that dot the landscape in North India in particular. Built by Maharaja Jagatjit Singh ji in 1930, the mosque is an exquisite testament to the love of the noble king for everything that he considered important to espouse his respect and admiration for various cultural and religious monuments.
The signature minaret and roofs are reminiscent of the mosques that dot the country of Morocco. In particular the Moorish mosque comes very much close to the mosque in Marakesh.
The walkway leading to the mosque once you enter the main gate is now full of whitish pebbles. I am sure it is quite a magical view in the presence of good lighting.
The corridors are very elegant and classy. It is not very large but gives you a feeling of generous space and room. The finely done carvings and sculptures are really great. I must also compliment the effort of the Archaeological Survey of India.
The neatly laid out lawns and landscaping outside has an unmistakable symmetry and reflects well on the meticulously planned and executed work on the inside.
The piece de resistance is the intricate artwork in the main dome. The ceiling artwork with the elegant chandelier gives an impression of an artful and delicate fountain about to spout water.
The calm and peaceful atmosphere is truly a tribute to the character of the mosque.
